##KOREAN WAR EPIDEMIC: Focus on investigation of Xintiandi church members'visit to Wuhan

I-CAIJING

CAIJING magazine official Wechat. "CAIJING" magazine, sponsored by the China Securities Market Research Center, was first published in 1998, adhering to the news concept of "independence, exclusiveness and originality" , and is known for authoritative, impartial and professional reporting, it is a must-read publication for policy-makers, researchers and managers in the field of politics and economics.

University of Edinburgh Medical School, a public health expert at the COVID-19, said the global outbreak has shown many unrelated outbreaks, which means that the pandemic has occurred, and governments should ensure the health system's ability to treat it, and educate the public to slow the spread.

By Cai Tingyi, CAIJING correspondent

Editor | Hao Zhou

"On behalf of our members, I would like to extend our sincerest apologies to all of you, " said Lee Man-Hee, the head of the new World Church, which has become a popular COVID-19 in South Korea.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
On March 2,89-year-old Lee Man-Hee of South Korea apologized at a news conference on the epidemic of new crown pneumonia held by the president of the new World Church, Lee Man-Hee. Figure / Fachen

On March 2, Lee Man-Hee held a press conference at the Gapyeong Study Center in Gyeonggi Province, an hour outside Seoul, vowing the church's full cooperation with the government in the fight against the outbreak. But this low profile did not last long. "Quiet! Order! " He could not resist revealing his attitude to the military management of his followers as protesters shouted at reporters asking questions.

The number of newly diagnosed cases in South Korea has increased by three figures every day, with 600 new cases added on March 3. The total number of confirmed cases quickly climbed to 4,812 within two weeks, of which 2,418 cases, or 57.4% , were related to the new World Church, 2,136 in the Church of Taegu.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
South Korean President Moon jae-in on March 3 declared a state of war, with all government departments on 24-hour standby to respond to the epidemic. The government will invest 30 trillion won (175.1 billion yuan) to fight the epidemic, at a press conference, he also apologized for the shortage of face masks in the country and promised that the government would improve the supply problem as soon as possible.

As the number of confirmed cases continues to climb, the anti-epidemic authorities announced that the opening of primary and secondary schools nationwide will be extended by two weeks from March 9 to March 23.

Moon's pledge was confirmed by virus experts, and Florian Krammer, a virologist and vaccine expert at the ICAHN School of Medicine in Mount Sinai, New York, said on social media that the escalation of response levels was an appropriate response to the epidemic.

Devi Sridhar, a public health expert at University of Edinburgh Medical School, told Caijing that the global outbreak has shown multiple unrelated outbreaks, which means that COVID-19 has become pandemic, governments should ensure the health-care capacity of health-care systems while educating people to slow transmission.

The legal responsibility of the new World Church

Since the outbreak of the disease in South Korea on February 21, the Church of Xintiandi's unwillingness to cooperate in handing over its membership list and accurate contact information is believed to be the main cause of the outbreak's difficulty in controlling, the related departments are seeking legal ways to hold the new world church accountable while being frustrated.

The Suwon District Attorney's office in Gyeonggi Province opened an investigation on March 1 into the church's role in the rapid spread of the epidemic, followed by the mayor of Taegu, Kwon young-jin, who has repeatedly given up false information because of the church, the Seoul Metropolitan Government also filed a complaint with the Seoul District Attorney's office, prosecutors were asked to indict Lee Man-Hee and 12 other local church leaders for murder and mayhem under South Korea's Infectious Disease Prevention and Control Act and the Criminal Code.

Park Won-soon, the mayor of the capital, Seoul, took to social media to urge South Korean prosecutors to arrest Lee Man-Hee. However, many South Korean lawyers believe that the "new world" church obstruction of the epidemic charges may be found, but murder charges may not be easy to establish.

The new coronavirus outbreak and the new World Church in South Korea have received their first attention due to the confirmed case of "No. 31" , a 61-year-old woman who attended numerous church activities after developing symptoms, resulting in an uncontrollable outbreak in South Korea, forced Korean society to face the negative impact of this mysterious church.

The South Korean government has shifted the focus of its investigation to the relationship between the new World Church and Wuhan. The South Korean Justice Ministry said Xintiandi had a branch in Wuhan and 42 members had visited the city since July last year. However, the church denied that the virus came from members of the Church in Wuhan. A statement from the church noted that 350 members of its Wuhan Branch had not entered the country since December 2019, and that "we hope the government will release the correct travel times for these 42 people. "

On March 3, South Korea's Central Disaster Safety Countermeasures Headquarters said that after comparing two members of Xintiandi who visited Wuhan in January this year, one of them was later confirmed in late February, it is still under investigation whether the member triggered a mass dissemination of the church. According to statistics, the new World Church in Taegu confirmed the main symptoms of the church at the time of February 7-10 and February 14-18; "31" case on February 17 diagnosed.

The government's epidemic prevention department has been actively contacting church members and conducting screening since mid February, but that has not been easy because church members tend to hide their identities. On February 24, Daegu western district health officials involved in the main epidemic area of the disease was confirmed infected with the virus, after he was confirmed that he is also a "new world" church members. The official was in charge of the region's overall epidemic prevention policy, and 50 staff members of the clinic were ordered to return home immediately to quarantine themselves after the diagnosis.

To the surprise of the outside world, 29.4% of confirmed cases were in the 20-30 age group, the highest of all age groups, and 62.4% were in women, compared with 37.6% in men. Analysis of the reasons, the epidemic prevention department estimated that as 20-30-year-old women are the main members of Xintiandi, so the confirmed case structure is particularly obvious. In addition, the Church confirmed the first case, the "31st case" in South Korea is a woman, and may also have more contact with women, resulting in infection of women far higher than men.

The church was founded in 1984 by Lee Man-Hee, who claimed to have a "non-bad body" and was known for his controversial methods of secretly proselytizing, in which believers were asked to infiltrate other churches without being identified. Believers believe that Lee Man-Hee is the second coming of Christ, that the church is the true heir, and that when Judgment Day comes it will lead them to heaven. According to believers who have attended church groups, Xintiandi is very strict about worshippers attending church services even if they are ill, and if they are absent, they will face different opinions from other believers.

In response to repeated accusations that the church was not cooperating in handing over its membership list, the Minister of the interior of the Church explained that the church handed over a list of 210,000 members on February 25, followed by a list of 65,000 members, including foreign believers, on February 27, in the middle because of the information gap caused misunderstanding.

Lee Man-Hee, 89, who has been in hiding since the church became aware of the outbreak, said he had been tested negative for the virus on Feb. 29. But South Korean officials said they could not confirm the results.

The Central Disaster Safety Response Department, which is responsible for the first round of screening, said on March 3 that it had completed a telephone survey of 190,000 members to determine if they had any symptoms, and that further virus screening would follow.

Tens of thousands of people have signed a petition calling for the church to be disbanded, but a church spokesman dismissed the church as a victim and accused outsiders of tarnishing it.

An English teacher at an elementary school near Taegu told Caijing she was very worried about the outbreak and "didn't have to go out. "

Longtime experts on the Church's culture question Lee Man-Hee's apology. Busan Presbyterian University professor Zhuo Zhiri pointed out that instead of apologizing to the public, what Lee Man-Hee should do is actually shout to his followers, he believes Lee Man-Hee's approach is more about maintaining his status among believers than it really is about cooperating with the epidemic.

"All should be collected" for confirmed patients

In Daegu, the cumulative number of confirmed cases remains the highest in the country, with 2,136 as of March 3, followed by 197 in North Gyeongsang Province, which has also been affected by the Xintiandi Church, of which 119 are related to Daegan Hospital. The highest incidence was in Daegu, with 126 confirmed cases per 100,000 people, followed by 23.4 cases per 100,000 people in North Gyeongsang Province, said Zheng Yinjing, head of the central epidemic prevention department.

The rapid increase in confirmed cases in Taegu has overwhelmed local medical institutions and left them as untreatable as Wuhan. As of March 1,1,661 patients had to wait in isolation at home for lack of beds, and four infected patients died while waiting.

In response to the new outbreak, the epidemic prevention department changed its strategy at the end of February to redistribute medical resources according to the severity of symptoms. Only the seriously ill were sent to hospitals for treatment, while the mildly ill were sent to additional temporary shelter hospitals.

To Save Time, the National Education and Training Center in Taegu was converted into the first Shelter Hospital, which opened on March 2 and treated 160 patients on the first day. The 17 medical staff of the resident centre take temperature twice a day for mild cases and examine their respiratory symptoms, and arrange for them to receive medical treatment if necessary. Unlike the Shelter Hospital in Wuhan, the center is operated by a joint government support group composed of relevant departments such as the Ministry of Administration and Security, the Ministry of National Defense, the Ministry of Health and Welfare (the Ministry of Health) , and the Daegu municipal government, daegu patients with mild infections each with a separate room.

Daegu Disaster Headquarters also opened a 24-hour hotline, arranged for specialized doctors to track the management of unadmitted confirmed patients, while ensuring that the required medication. Taegu's mayor said at a press conference on March 1 that avoiding the death of a confirmed patient while waiting for a bed would be a priority for the next phase of the epidemic.

Later this week, the North Gyeongsang Province region will also open two shelter hospitals, renovating the Samsung Manpower Development Hospital in Yeongdeok County and the Seoul National University Talent Hospital in Mungyeong, with 203 and 100 wards, respectively. The Central Government's epidemic prevention department said it would send more medical staff and resources to the heavily infected region of Taegu to try to relocate 1,000 patients to a new shelter hospital this week.
